#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi.rst:26
msgid "KHO persistent memory tracker ABI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:181
msgid ""
"KHO tracks preserved memory using a radix tree data structure. Each node of "
"the tree is exactly a single page. The leaf nodes are bitmaps where each set "
"bit is a preserved page of any order. The intermediate nodes are tables of "
"physical addresses that point to a lower level node."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:186
msgid "The tree hierarchy is shown below::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:205
msgid ""
"The tree is traversed using a key that encodes the page's physical address "
"(pa) and its order into a single unsigned long value. The encoded key value "
"is composed of two parts: the 'order bit' in the upper part and the 'shifted "
"physical address' in the lower part.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:219
msgid ""
"Shifted Physical Address: The 'shifted physical address' is the physical "
"address normalized for its order. It effectively represents the PFN shifted "
"right by the order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:223
msgid ""
"Order Bit: The 'order bit' encodes the page order by setting a single bit at "
"a specific position. The position of this bit itself represents the order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:227
msgid ""
"For instance, on a 64-bit system with 4KB pages (PAGE_SHIFT = 12), the "
"maximum range for the shifted physical address (for order 0) is 52 bits (64 "
"- 12). This address occupies bits [0-51]. For order 0, the order bit is set "
"at position 52."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:232
msgid ""
"The following diagram illustrates how the encoded key value is split into "
"indices for the tree levels, with PAGE_SIZE of 4KB::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:240
msgid ""
"The radix tree stores pages of all orders in a single 6-level hierarchy. It "
"efficiently shares higher tree levels, especially due to common zero top "
"address bits, allowing a single, efficient algorithm to manage all pages. "
"This bitmap approach also offers memory efficiency; for example, a 512KB "
"bitmap can cover a 16GB memory range for 0-order pages with PAGE_SIZE = 4KB."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../core-api/kho/abi:28: ../include/linux/kho/abi/kexec_handover.h:247
msgid ""
"The data structures defined here are part of the KHO ABI. Any modification "
"to these structures that breaks backward compatibility must be accompanied "
"by an update to the \"compatible\" string. This ensures that a newer kernel "
"can correctly interpret the data passed by an older kernel."
msgstr ""

